–$5,900</td></tr><tr><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29328664?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">GIA 1.00ct D-VVS2</a></strong></td><td>Ideal</td><td>D</td><td>VVS2</td><td><strong>$4,758</strong></td><td>$5,200–$5,700</td></tr><tr><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29358987?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">GIA 1.00ct D-VVS1</a></strong></td><td>Ideal</td><td>D</td><td>VVS1</td><td><strong>$6,230</strong></td><td>$6,600–$7,100</td></tr><tr><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29054155?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">GIA 1.00ct D-IF</a></strong></td><td>Ideal</td><td>D</td><td>IF</td><td><strong>$7,578</strong></td><td>$8,000–$9,000</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Reading the table:** The "Ring Total (Solitaire)" column adds a $400–$900 solitaire setting to the stone price. These are the complete ring costs — the price you pay at Blue Nile for the finished 1ct pear shaped diamond ring delivered to your door. For halo or sidestone settings, add $700–$2,670 more to the stone price for the setting upgrade.

The most important data point in this table: the G-VVS2 Ideal at $3,849 is only $46 more than the D-VS1 at $3,803. G color is indistinguishable from D color in most lighting conditions when the stone is set in a ring — the pear's elongated facet pattern distributes color evenly. D vs G color at 1ct is a laboratory distinction that has no visible consequence in everyday wear.

At the same time, VVS2 clarity is two grades above VS1. The G-VVS2 delivers more clarity at approximately the same price as the D-VS1. Both are outstanding 1ct pear shaped diamonds, but the G-VVS2 is the higher-value purchase for buyers who prioritize objectivity over grade prestige.

## The Elongation Dividend

A 1ct pear shaped diamond is not the same size as a 1ct round diamond. The pear's elongated silhouette — typically 8.5mm long by 5.7mm wide at a 1.50–1.60 L/W ratio — creates more finger coverage than any other 1ct brilliant cut stone. A 1ct round diamond measures approximately 6.5mm in diameter. A 1ct pear at 8.5×5.7mm covers 48.45mm² of face-up surface compared to the round's 33.18mm², a 46% difference in visible surface area.

This is the Elongation Dividend: buyers of a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring receive a stone that looks substantially larger than its stated carat weight would suggest. Pear diamonds are cut to prioritize face-up size over total depth, distributing mass toward the girdle plane where it is visible rather than hiding it below the table. A well-proportioned 1ct pear in a solitaire setting presents as a clearly elongated center stone that reads visually closer to 1.3–1.5ct in a round.

**What the Elongation Dividend means for ring selection:**

- A 1ct pear in a solitaire setting is already a visually bold ring. Buyers who want a "big ring" do not need to jump to 2ct in the pear category the way they might with round diamonds.
- For halo settings, the Elongation Dividend is compounded — a halo adds perimeter coverage to a stone already wider than its carat weight implies. The result at 1ct can look like a 1.8–2ct center stone.
- For buyers comparing a 1ct round and a 1ct pear at the same price: the pear offers more visual stone for the money in nearly all settings.

![The Elongation Dividend: why a 1ct pear diamond looks bigger than a 1ct round — 48.5mm² vs 33.2mm² face-up area, +46% more coverage](/images/bn-pear-1ct-1.avif)

The Elongation Dividend is also why 1ct pear diamonds are the most popular choice for pear-shaped pendants: the elongated silhouette creates a natural drop effect, longer than a round or cushion solitaire pendant at the same carat weight, which reads as more substantial on the chain. See the [Pear Diamond Pendant Guide](/pear-diamond-pendant) for pendant-specific setting options and pricing at Blue Nile.

## 1 Carat Pear Diamond Ring Settings at Blue Nile

The 1 carat pear diamond ring price is a combination of two separate purchases: the loose 1ct pear diamond stone and the ring setting. Blue Nile sells both components and assembles the finished ring before shipping. Setting prices for pear diamond rings range from under $500 for a basic solitaire to over $4,000 for a platinum halo with sidestones.

**Solitaire settings for 1ct pear diamonds ($400–$900):**
The pear solitaire is the cleanest, most popular setting for a 1ct pear shaped diamond. A five-prong pear solitaire (four prongs plus a V-tip prong at the pointed end) in 14K white gold costs $400–$700 at Blue Nile. The V-tip prong is specific to pear diamonds — it protects the fragile pointed tip from chipping while keeping the stone visible.

In 18K white gold, the same solitaire setting runs $600–$900. Platinum solitaires for 1ct pear diamonds start at $800+. The solitaire is the recommended setting for showcasing the full Elongation Dividend — no additional metal or side stones interrupt the pear's silhouette.

**Sidestone settings for 1ct pear diamonds ($1,100–$2,200):**
A sidestone setting adds small side diamonds alongside the pear center stone, flanking the pear's shoulder arcs. The [Pear Sidestone Diamond Engagement Ring in 14K Yellow Gold (1/4 ct. tw.) at $1,820](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-4-ct-tw-item-192877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry point in the sidestone category. Combined with the D-VS1 natural pear at $3,803, the complete ring total is $5,623. The sidestone style adds presence without the visual complexity of a halo.

**Halo settings for 1ct pear diamonds ($1,800–$4,005):**
Pear halo rings surround the center stone with a frame of smaller diamonds, visually enlarging the pear center. The [Pear Shape Side Stone Diamond Halo Engagement Ring in 14K White Gold at $3,570](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-310842?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the [same ring in Platinum at $4,005](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-310847?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are Blue Nile's primary pear halo options. A 1ct pear + D-VS1 stone in the 14K halo totals $7,373; with the IGI D-VVS1 lab pear at $1,006, the halo ring total is $4,576 — a complete high-impact ring under $5,000.

For a full breakdown of every setting style available for pear diamonds, see the [Pear Diamond Engagement Ring Guide](/pear-diamond-engagement-ring).

## The Ring Total Formula

The Ring Total Formula is the correct method for pricing a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring: **Ring Total = Stone Price + Setting Price.** These are two separate line items at Blue Nile — buyers select the loose diamond and the ring setting independently and add both to cart. The finished ring is assembled and shipped together.

The mistake many buyers make: researching only the stone price, then encountering sticker shock at checkout when the setting is added. A 1ct pear shaped diamond at $3,803 is not a complete ring. The Ring Total Formula ensures the full budget is allocated correctly.

