e.com/diamond-details/29054155?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">GIA D-IF Ideal</a></strong></td><td>GIA</td><td>Natural</td><td><strong>$7,578</strong></td><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-310847?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">Platinum Halo $4,005</a></td><td>~$11,583</td><td>Best natural 1ct pear ring; D-IF, platinum halo, top-tier build</td></tr></tbody></table>

## Final Verdict: Which 1ct Pear Shaped Diamond Ring to Buy

**Best natural 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring under $4,500:** [GIA D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + 14K solitaire setting at $400–$600. Ring total $4,200–$4,400. D colorless, VS1 eye-clean under all lighting conditions, Ideal cut, GIA certified. This is the correct natural 1ct pear engagement ring for buyers who want the best grade-to-price ratio with no compromises on certification or cut quality.

**Best value natural 1ct pear ring:** [GIA G-VVS2 Ideal at $3,849](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28866691?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). G color in a mounted pear ring looks identical to D in everyday wear. VVS2 clarity is the top clarity tier with eye-visible confirmation of flawless appearance. At $3,849 vs $3,803 — a $46 premium — you receive a stone two clarity grades above VS1. This is the objectively better purchase.

**Best lab grown 1ct pear ring under $2,000:** [IGI D-VVS1 Ideal at $1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + 14K solitaire. Ring total $1,400–$1,600. D colorless, VVS1 clarity, Ideal cut. The same grade in natural costs $6,230 for the stone alone. This is the single most efficient 1ct pear ring buy in either natural or lab grown categories.

**Best lab grown 1ct pear ring (GIA certified):** [GIA D-VVS1 Ideal at $1,073](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23489206?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Same grade tier, GIA certification at $67 more than the IGI entry. For buyers who want GIA documentation on their lab grown stone, this is the path.

**Best 1ct pear ring for halo setting:** [GIA E-VVS2 Ideal at $4,236](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28301339?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [14K white gold halo at $3,570](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-310842?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = $7,806 total. E color, VVS2 clarity, halo adds perimeter diamonds. In a halo, this 1ct pear reads face-up at 1.6–1.8ct equivalent presence.

## Expert Summary

> The 1ct pear shaped diamond ring is a genuinely excellent choice for almost every buyer in this category, and I want to explain why specifically: the Elongation Dividend is real and it is one of the most underappreciated advantages in diamond buying. A 1ct pear gives you more finger coverage than a 1ct round. Buyers who fixate on carat weight as a proxy for size are leaving the pear's biggest advantage on the table. The people who understand this end up with rings that look larger than their price would suggest.
>
> On the 1ct vs 1.5ct question for natural diamonds: the jump from $3,803 to $8,000–$12,000 for the same grade is real. Unless your budget genuinely supports 1.5ct at the grade you want, the 1ct pear at $3,803 is the correct purchase. For lab grown, the 1ct to 1.5ct jump is about $500–$1,000 on the stone — there, I'd look at 1.5ct seriously if your total ring budget is over $2,500.
>
> The thing I always tell buyers: check the 360° video before purchasing any pear diamond. You cannot see the bow-tie in photographs. The video is the only way to evaluate this — and a severe bow-tie on a 1ct pear ruins the Elongation Dividend completely.
>
> — Farzana Hasan, Fine Jewelry Analyst

## Frequently Asked Questions

### How much does a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring cost?

A 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring costs $4,200–$9,000+ for a natural GIA stone with a setting, depending on grade. The natural stone ranges from $3,803 (D-VS1 Ideal) to $7,578 (D-IF Ideal); a 14K solitaire setting adds $400–$700. Lab grown 1ct pear diamond rings cost $1,400–$2,500 total (stone $1,006–$1,548 + setting).

### What is the best 1 carat pear shaped diamond?

The best value 1ct pear shaped diamond for a ring is the [GIA G-VVS2 Ideal at $3,849](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28866691?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). G color looks identical to D in a set ring; VVS2 clarity is exceptionally clean; Ideal cut maximizes the pear's face-up spread. For buyers who specifically want D colorless: [GIA D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the correct entry.

### What does a 1 carat pear shaped diamond look like on the hand?

A 1ct pear shaped diamond ring is more visually striking than a 1ct round ring on the hand. At approximately 8.5×5.7mm, the pear covers more finger length than a 6.5mm round. In a solitaire, the teardrop silhouette is distinctive and elongates the appearance of the finger. In a halo, the 1ct pear center with a surrounding diamond frame reads as a 1.8–2ct equivalent presence.

### What color should a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring be?

D–G color for white gold or platinum settings. H is the minimum for white metal. For yellow or rose gold settings, G–J color is acceptable — the warm metal neutralizes any stone warmth. The recommendation for the best value: G color, which looks identical to D in a set ring and saves $400–$2,400+ on the stone price versus D at the same clarity grade.

### What L/W ratio is best for a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring?

1.55–1.65 is the recommended L/W ratio for a 1ct pear in a standard solitaire or halo engagement ring. This produces the classic elongated teardrop silhouette with balanced proportions. Below 1.45, the pear looks stubby. Above 1.75, the stone looks narrow. East-west pear settings work best at 1.40–1.55. Calculate from the stone's listed mm dimensions: length ÷ width.

### How big does a 1 carat pear diamond look?

A 1ct pear diamond measures approximately 8.5×5.7mm at a standard 1.60 L/W ratio, covering about 48mm² face-up — compared to 33mm² for a 1ct round at 6.5mm diameter. The pear provides 46% more visible face-up surface area than a round at the same carat weight. In a ring, a 1ct pear reads visually as approximately 1.3–1.4ct equivalent in comparison to rounds.

### What is a 1.5 carat pear shaped diamond ring price?

A 1.5ct pear shaped diamond ring costs approximately $8,500–$14,000 for a natural GIA stone with a solitaire setting. Natural 1.5ct pear stones run $8,000–$12,000 depending on grade and availability. Lab grown 1.5ct pear diamond rings cost $1,900–$2,800 total — a modest jump from the 1ct lab grown range of $1,400–$2,000. For current 1.5ct availability, filter Blue Nile's [pear diamond search](https://www.bluenile.com/diamonds/pear-shaped?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) by 1.40–1.60ct.

### Should I buy a 1ct or 1.5ct pear shaped diamond ring?

For natural diamonds: the 1ct pear ring at $4,200–$4,700 total is the right choice unless your budget clearly supports $8,500–$14,000 for 1.5ct. The quality difference at the same grade is minimal; the size difference (8.5×5.7mm vs 10.0×6.7mm) is real but the pear's Elongation Dividend already makes 1ct look larger than its carat weight. For lab grown diamonds: upgrade to 1.5ct if your budget allows — the price difference is $500–$800 on the stone, which is meaningful but not prohibitive.

### Is a pear diamond ring good for everyday wear?

Yes, with the correct setting. The pointed tip of a pear diamond requires a V-prong (pointed prong) for protection — this is standard on all pear settings at Blue Nile. The V-prong prevents chipping at the tip, which is the most fragile part of the pear silhouette. With a properly set V-prong, a 1ct pear diamond ring handles daily wear without concern. The bezel setting (metal rim encircling the stone) provides additional protection for active lifestyles. See the [Pear Shaped Solitaire Diamond Ring Guide](/pear-shaped-solitaire-diamond-ring) for prong count and setting security details.

### What is a good clarity for a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring?

VS1 or VS2 are the recommended clarity grades for a 1ct pear diamond ring — both are eye-clean (no inclusions visible to the naked eye) and avoid the premium of VVS2 or higher. The [GIA D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the clarity-safe entry for natural stones. For buyers with room in their budget, VVS2 delivers top-tier clarity at a modest premium — the [G-VVS2 at $3,849](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28866691?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is only $46 more than VS1.

### Does a 1 carat pear diamond have a bow-tie?

All pear diamonds have some degree of bow-tie — a dark shadow across the center of the stone that results from the cutting geometry of the pear brilliant pattern. The severity ranges from faint (barely visible, does not affect beauty) to severe (a broad dark band that reduces brilliance). Grade tier does not predict bow-tie severity — a D-IF Ideal cut pear can have a noticeable bow-tie while a G-VS1 has a faint one. The only way to evaluate bow-tie is to watch the 360° video on each stone's product page at Blue Nile. Never purchase a 1ct pear diamond ring without watching the video.

### What is the best setting for a 1 carat pear shaped diamond ring?

The five-prong solitaire (four prongs + V-tip) in 14K white gold is the most popular and recommended setting for a 1ct pear shaped diamond ring. It showcases the full Elongation Dividend, secures the stone with the V-tip prong at the point, and keeps the total ring cost under $4,500. For buyers who want more visual impact, the [14K white gold halo at $3,570](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-310842?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) adds perimeter diamonds that amplify the pear center's presence significantly. See the [Pear Diamond Halo Ring Guide](/pear-diamond-halo-ring) for every pear halo style at Blue Nile.

### What is a 1ct pear shaped diamond pendant price?

A 1ct pear shaped diamond pendant costs $4,000–$5,600 for a natural GIA stone (stone $3,803–$5,000 + pendant setting $200–$600). For a lab grown 1ct pear pendant: $1,200–$2,150 total (stone $1,006–$1,548 + pendant setting $200–$600). The pear pendant benefits from the same Elongation Dividend as the ring — a 1ct pear pendant hangs longer on the chain than any other 1ct shape pendant. See the [Pear Diamond Pendant Guide](/pear-diamond-pendant) for current pendant settings and prices.

